SS_FolderEntries.description_text: The purpose of this RFP is to solicit proposals for the complete renovation and refurbishment of the SCOPE arena. This renovation project is part of a long term, strategic plan for the development of new and/or renovation of old public assembly facilities for the entire city. The City is seeking proposals for improvements to the existing 10,000 seat Scope arena or alternative recommendations for its refurbishment, including possible demolition and rebuilding. The first phase of services shall include a feasibility study that will analyze program, design options, and full development costs. A successful consultant team shall be composed of nationally recognized professionals with experience in arena design, urban planning, architectural and engineering design, transportation planning and analysis, and accounting and financial planning and analysis. The initial contract shall be for the performance of the feasibility study. The City retains the option of extending the feasibility study to include full design and construction services related to the construction and renovations to SCOPE, traffic studies, and other work as may be necessary for an analysis of current public assembly facilities and future needs.

Wisconsin Electric Power Company (WE) issued a request for proposals (RFP) for up to 75 MW of renewable and offered power purchase agreements (PPA) of five to 10-years. WE said it would accept individual projects as small as 1 MW and in all cases will reserve a "call on the associated energy." Projects larger than 1 MW are preferred, WE noted. Although bids from facilities located in Wisconsin will be given preference, bids from outside of Wisconsin will also be considered.
Any renewable resource on-line after May 11, 2004 may be considered.
The 75 MW RFP supersedes an open-ended RFP for up to 5 MW of renewable energy previously issued in March, WE stressed. And, the utility noted, the 75 MW RFP is not part of a recently issued an RFP for 250 MW of dispatchable capacity, together with a call on the associated energy, to be built in eastern Wisconsin. The RFP does not change WE's plan to build two utility-scale wind turbines in 2005.
For the 75 MW RFP, renewable energy resources can include wind, biomass, solar/photovoltaic (PV), hydroelectric, geothermal, fuel cells utilizing renewable fuels and landfill gas. However, WE said the following energy sources do not qualify for this RFP: hydroelectric facilities larger than 30 MW, and; biomass facilities that derive energy from incineration of tires, garbage, general household, institutional and commercial non-wood waste, industrial lunchroom or office waste, landscape waste, or chemically contaminated construction and demolition debris.
WE will assess all submitted responses to determine which are the most economical, feasible and viable options for meeting WE's generation needs. The assessment will take into account both price and non-price factors. WE may develop a preliminary short list of potential suppliers and at some point in the process, WE may provide a selected group of respondents with a model PPA for preliminary contract discussions.

February 7, 2003

To whom it may concern:

The Seattle Monorail Project is pleased to present a Draft Request for Qualifications (“RFQ”) to the public and potential teams interested in submitting proposals to design, build, operate and maintain the Seattle Monorail Green Line (the "Green Line "), through one or more contracts (collectively, the “DBOM Contract”) to be entered into with the Seattle Monorail Project pursuant to RCW 35.95A.050. The Seattle Monorail Project is issuing this Draft RFQ to allow the public and potential teams to comment on the proposed requirements for submittal of Qualifications to compete in a proposal process for being the selected Contractor for the DBOM Contract.

The Draft RFQ will be available on the Seattle Monorail Project’s official website: www.elevated.org. Printed copies of the Draft RFQ will also be made available. Please contact the SMP at (206) 382-1220 or at info@elevated.org.

In addition, the Seattle Monorail Project will hold a public workshop on Tuesday, February 11, 2003 at 1:30 PST, in the Shaw Room, which is located in the Northwest Rooms Conference Center on the north side of the Key Arena. The RFQ/RFP process will be generally described and prospective respondents and members of the public may ask questions and make comments regarding the Draft RFQ at the workshop.

The Seattle Monorail Project will also accept written questions and comments on the Draft RFQ. Any such correspondence must be received not later than 5:00 p.m. on February 20, 2003 and addressed to:

The Seattle Monorail Project
1904 Third Avenue, Suite 525
Seattle WA 98101
Attn: Tom Horkan, Director of Construction

The Seattle Monorail Project intends to issue a final Request for Qualifications in early March 2003 and will include a minimum sixty (60) day period for preparation of Qualification Submittals.

From time to time, the Seattle Monorail Project may post requests for information on the website to obtain input on design issues to support the Green Line EIS process and urge you to monitor and assist us as you can.

The terms of the Draft RFQ are intended to provide maximum opportunity for competition, encourage creativity and new ideas, and maximize the opportunity of teams to form that meet the requirements of the Plan within the project schedule. The Seattle Monorail Project looks forward to receiving and reviewing industry and public comments on the Draft RFQ.

The Seattle Monorail Project looks forward to working with the public and interested DBOM teams in the successful development of the Green Line.

Sincerely,
Seattle Monorail Project

SS_FolderEntries.title: View the Help web site on the Internet

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
SiteScape provides two discussion forums on the Internet that you can use to assist you with installation, configuration, trouble shooting, and customization. Just view the web page, register a username, and begin participating.

Click on the linked header of the web page you wish to access:

Support Forum
Use this forum to assist with installation, configuration, trouble shooting issues, and reports of product defects.

Customization Forum
Use this forum to assist with your efforts to use workflow processes, custom commands, templates, and object overloads. (For more information about workflow, custom commands, and templates, see the manager's Help system. For more information about object overloads, see the Toolkit Help system.)
SS_FolderEntries.title: Participate in our support and customization forums

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
Please add a reply to this topic. Introduce yourself, and mention any questions that you hope to have answered by participating in this forum. (If you are the first manager to view this forum, do not be concerned that you are currently the only participant. A topic that follows tells you how to delegate management duties, which will allow others to participate in this forum with you.)

Consider adding two topics to every discussion forum in your zone, as follows:

  • A topic describing the purpose of the discussion, including any guidelines for participation.

  • A "sign in" topic, so that people know who is participating in a particular discussion.

After you add your introduction, click on the Manager tutorial for [your organization] link in the upper-left corner of the page to return to the list of topics, and then click on the linked title of the third topic, Configuration choices.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Please click here to sign in

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
SiteScape understands the excitement involved in purchasing and installing new software. For that reason, we have included the following forums in your zone workspace that you can use and explore right away:

  • The user tutorial forum

  • The management forum (this forum)

  • A general-purpose discussion forum

  • A general-purpose calendar

  • A general-purpose chat room

With the exception of this management forum, anyone who can access your zone has the right to view and use these forums. So, the content of these forums should be applicable to all members of your organization.

In additon to helping you get started right away, we understand that you will want to shape and mold your Forum installation so that it meets the unique needs of your organization. The replies that follow explain the different levels of configuration and customization that you can apply to Forum.

We recommend that you implement at least the second level, because it provides valuable assistance to your users; also, there are a few features of Forum that your users will not be able to access until you complete this level.

Then, you can either implement the other levels over time, implement them all at once, or choose not to implement them at all. As always, we recommend that the needs, work styles, and work requirements of your users guide your configuration and customization process.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Configuration choices

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
After installation, you can view and use the user tutorial and the mangement forum (this forum). These forums are populated (contain information to get people started) and contain clear instructions for their use.

The three general-purpose forums contain no information. We recommend that you complete Level 2 configuration, which includes populating these general-purpose forums with enough information to get your users started.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Level 1: Use Forum "out of the box"

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
After you complete this level of configuration, all of the five initially provided forums are fully configured and clearly documented, and all of Forum's basic features are turned on. This level of configuration should take no more than an hour of your time, and it will assist your users immensely.

Topic 4 lists the steps for this configuration level and provides a brief description of each step.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Level 2: Initial configuration

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
This level of configuration involves the further population of your zone.

No single discussion forum or chat room can accommodate all of the broad topic areas that people in your organization will want to discuss. For example, one or more of Forum's specialized forums may be useful within your organization; specialized forums are customized discussion forums that have additional tools for tracking resumes, moderating discussions, sales account management, help-desk work, and more.

As another example, people may want you to create forums whose participants are limited to a subgroup within your organization. Or they may request a team workspace so that their team can use a set of forums in a space that is private to their group.

You can use the Wizards page to create new discussion forums, specialized forums, chat rooms, workspaces, or team workspaces. Topic 5 discusses issues involved in the creation of new workspaces, and the online Help for managers provides complete information about creating forums and workspaces.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Level 3: Create additional forums and workspaces

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
This level begins your customization of Forum. To perform customizations at this level, managers fill out easy-to-use HTML forms within discussion forums; no programming is required.

Here are the types of customizations that you can perform at this level:

Custom commands
Custom commands are commands on the Add menu within discussion forums that you design and that correspond to the exact types of information that your users need to enter into Forum to do their jobs.

To illustrate the power of this level of customization, we will discuss examples from the Resume Tracker forum. The Resume Tracker is one of the specialized forums that ships with our product, and it provides online tools for the storing, review, follow-up, and processing of resumes. The Resume Tracker includes customizations developed by SiteScape.

So, for example, when you click on the Add toolbar item in a Resume Tracking forum, you do not see commands to create the four default entry types: discussions, documents, URLs, or surveys. The only command you see is the "Add a Resume" command. SiteScape customized this forum by removing standard commands from the menu and adding a custom command ("Add a Resume").

Workflow Processes
A Workflow process defines a specific set of users who have the right to work on an entry in a discussion forum, and defines an orderly and predictable process through which the entry must pass.

For example, once you add a resume to a Resume Tracking forum, the entry automatically enters the "New" workflow state. So, when you view the folder listing, you see a new column in the folder table ("State") and a value for your newly created entry ("New").

The Resume Tracking forum defines a workflow process that moves a resume from "New" to any of the following states: "Phone Screen," "First Interview," or "Do Not Hire." Reviewing the forum's folder listing, you can tell at a glance at which step in the process a particular resume currently resides, providing an online organization system for your hiring process.

In addition to labeling the steps in the process, Forum's workflow feature can automatically send reminder e-mail messages. For example, you can set up Forum so that when an administrative assistant enters a resume in the system, Forum then places it in the "New" state and automatically sends e-mail to inform the hiring manager that a new resume requires her attention before it can move to the next step in the process.

The examples in this reply discuss a custom command and workflow process that we provide for you "out of the box." To use them, simply use the Wizards page to create a Resume Tracking forum.

If you choose, you can modify the pre-defined custom commands and workflow processes in the specialized discussion forums, or you can develop completely new custom commands and workflow processes that exactly match the way that your users do their jobs.

We recommend that you give members of your organization some time to learn the default Forum features. Then, we recommend that you consult with your users about the types of work that they would like to automate online. Finally, you can use Forum's easy-to-use HTML forms to develop highly customized and powerful custom commands and workflow processes that will create forums that appear as if Forum was designed specifically for use in your organization.

For more information about custom commands and workflow processes, see the online Help system for managers.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Level 4: Developing custom commands and workflow processes

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
For all desired customizations that cannot be accomplished using custom commands and workflow processes, you must use templates.

Templates are HTML files that allow programmers to alter the look-and-feel or behavior of one or more forums. Template files contain standard HTML tags and Tcl code, the alteration of which allows programmers to make very broad and powerful changes to one or more forums (potentially creating new Forum applications). Programmers can do this without working on the server machine and without working with the product's source files. Once templates are created or modified, you can implement them or go back to the factory default with a few clicks of the mouse on Forum's template-management pages.

To use templates to their full ability, we recommend that you have experience working with programming languages. (Tcl is a programming language very much like C in its syntax.)

For more information about templates, see the manager's Help system.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Level 5: Customizations using templates

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
To make advanced customizations, programmers can work directly with Forum's source files, which ship with our product. Use this level of customization for any changes to Forum that you cannot implement using templates.

Forum's source files are comprised of standard Tcl commands and Forum-specific Toolkit commands. Forum uses an object oriented paradigm that allows programmers to write "object overloads" without having to edit Forum's sources directly and that are not overwritten with subsequent updates to the Forum product.

For more information about Forum sources, Tcl, and the Toolkit, see the Toolkit Help system.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Level 6: Advanced customizations

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
First, remember that you can implement powerful customizations using custom commands and workflow processes. Try to implement your customization using those HTML-based features, and use SiteScape's Customization forum for assistance.

Then, if you would like to make a customization to your installation of Forum that requires work with templates or object overloads, and if your organization does not include programming expertise, SiteScape's customization team is available to do contract work for you.

For contract quotes and other information about our customization services, please contact our friendly sales people at this address: sales@sitescape.com
SS_FolderEntries.title: "What if I'm not a programmer?!"

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
The replies that follow present you with the initial configuration steps required to document the forums that initially ship with the product and to turn on all of the basic Forum features.

The purpose of this topic is to give you a general overview of the work that needs to be done for this level of configuration. For specific information on how to complete each of these steps, see the online Help system for managers.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Initial configuration steps

SS_FolderEntries.description_text: To do this, log in as wf_admin or as a member of the SSF Administrators group.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Log in as a zone manager

SS_FolderEntries.description_text: By default, anonymous users can access your zone workspace. If you choose, you can turn this off, so that only registered users are granted access.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Set access to the zone workspace

SS_FolderEntries.description_text: By default, anonymous users have the right to register themselves. If you want more control of the registration of users, you can disable this feature. If you do this, then people must contact a zone manager, and the zone manager must register a username for the person.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Set access to the user database

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
If you already know that very large subgroups within your organization will probably want their own forums or workspaces, you can create these groups. (For example, the Marketing Department, the Engineering Department, Executive Management, and so forth.)

We recommend that you do not create too many groups before you read the hardcopy manual, Getting the Most Out of Forum, which is described in a reply that follows.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Create groups

SS_FolderEntries.description_text: You can turn off or turn on certain Forum features. For example, you can disable the ability of users to create their own personal calendars (if you are concerned about many unused personal calendars wasting disk space). Or, if your organization finds chatting to be incompatible with your organization's culture, you can disable chat rooms.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Disable access to Forum features

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
You need to provide the name of your e-mail server before Forum's e-mail notifications and "Send Mail" features can work.

E-mail notifications are e-mail messages that Forum sends to users periodically, which contain information about and links to new or modified entries in a discussion forum. In this way, users can keep track of recent activity in important discussion forums.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Specify your e-mail server

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
In your zone workspace, you can add a company logo. Or, on the zone workspace's page, you can add text at the top that welcomes or instructs users, or "postamble" text that provides information (for example, you can add a link to your organization's home page in the postamble).

In the general-purpose forums (the discussion forum, calendar, and chat room), you can change their titles so that they reflect their purpose. For example, you can change the discussion forum's title to "Widget Company General Discussion."

Here are some other simple changes that you can make to create a more welcoming collaboration environment in the forums provided in the zone workspace by default:

  • Add text to the top folder of the general-purpose discussion that welcomes and instructs the users.

  • Add a "purpose of this discussion" and "sign in" topic to the general-purpose discussion.

  • Add another topic of interest to the discussion to "get things going."

  • Add entries to the general-purpose calendar, such as company holidays.

  • Create a chat room whose purpose will immediately be clear to your users (for example, "Monthly Company Chat" or "Monthly New Product Update"), and schedule at least one chat session during which users can try this feature.

  • Add topics to the user tutorial that provide tips for using calendars, chat rooms, messaging, or specialty forums.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Configure your zone workspace and general-purpose forums

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
Before users can receive e-mail notifications, you need to access each discussion forum separately, establish a schedule that Forum uses for sending notifications (for example, every work day at 9 o'clock, 1 o'clock, and 4 o'clock), and establish a default style.

See the online Help for managers to read more information about how to do this step and about possible notificaton styles.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Enable e-mail notifications

SS_FolderEntries.description_text: Now that the forums are documented and Forum's features are all enabled, use the Wizards page to invite users to the zone.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Invite users to the zone

SS_FolderEntries.description_text: Once users register, you can add them to the appropriate groups that you created in an earlier step. (If you have not yet created groups, you can skip this step.)
SS_FolderEntries.title: Add users to groups

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
By default, the Toolkit Help does not exist. To create it, you need to go the Help system for Managers, click on the Administer button in the toolbar frame, and then click on the Create the SiteScape Toolkit Help Facility link.

If you plan on trying template customizations, you will want to look at the Toolkit Help for instruction on Tcl and Toolkit commands.

If someone clicks on the Toolkit Help button before you create the system, Forum displays a brief page that states that the Toolkit Help system does not exist.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Create the Toolkit Help

SS_FolderEntries.description_text: The Help system for managers contains information about other management tasks that you may want to consider, such as delegating the management of workspaces and forums, and using custom commands and workflow processes. We recommend that you at least skim this material.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Learn about next steps

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
This book contains very helpful information about tailoring the installation of Forum to your organization's needs, ways to encourage greater use of Forum, and other information about maximizing the potential of this collaboration tool.

If you are part of an enterprise organization (a very large organization, possibly spanning a large geography), then we would like to strongly recommend that you read this manual, because setting up Forum for maximum use in very large organizations requires more thought and planning than for smaller organizations.

Topic 5 briefly discusses one of the issues covered in greater detail in Getting the Most Out of Forum. Review that topic to get a general understanding of the type of material covered in that book.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Read Getting the Most Out of Forum

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
One of the most powerful features of Forum is the ability to populate and customize your zone in whatever way best suits your organization's needs. So, our product was designed not to impose either an "organizational" or a "procedural" structure on you or your users.

In one respect, there is tremendous freedom and power in the Forum design. In another respect, the sparsely populated single zone that users see when they first log in will not serve the needs of a very large, enterprise organization for very long.

This topic provides information for the zone manager who must create a workspace hierarchy, delegated management, a user community, and other Forum infrastructure for an enterprise organization. (However, managers of small organizations may benefit from reading this information as well.) Also, this topic is abreviated from a chapter in the Getting the Most Out of Forum book; if you want to read more detail about the workspace structures described in this topic, please read that manual.

The following replies provide two methods for structuring your workspace hierarchy. You can read the examples to stimulate thought and then develop your own structure. Or, you can implement the structure that most closely meets the needs of your organization.

Finally, remember that a robust and effective structure that matches the needs of your organization can only develop over time and with the active assistance of your users; one of the structures presented in the following sections is the result of three years of modifications before finally arriving at an optimum structure. Was it worth the effort? As a consequence of developing this structure, this enterprise organization estimates that the use of SiteScape's collaboration software saved them approximately $200 million in expense in the year 2000 alone.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Planning workspace hierarchies

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
The enterprise organization that developed this structure wanted information to flow between people who were all performing in a broad category of "job function." The idea is that people performing work on similar types of services and products need to collaborate and share most often.

In addition to structuring the workspace hierarchies so that people collaborate efficiently within job function, this organization developed an effective way to delegate the management of workspaces. This structure requires significant effort toward the beginning of the process, but it saves time and effort later; it assists in the smooth transition of workspace managers and it facilitates various levels of user access to newly created forums.

The replies that follow provide you with a step list for implementing this type of structure using Forum and a summary of the benefits of this method.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Structured by job function

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
The following are steps required to implement this workspace structure (they are explained in more detail in the Getting the Most Out of Forum book):

  1. Make a list of job functions.

    The most important aspects of this list are that membership in those groups is considered to be integral to successful delivery of a service or product line, and that your users strongly consider themselves to be members of the groups on your list. In many cases, this will be the list of large departments in your organization.

    The items in your completed list correspond to workspaces that you will create.

    Here are some tips for creating this list:

    • Keep your list as short as possible.

    • Keep your hierarchy as "flat" as possible.

    • Do not organize by geography.

      Several of our large customers have found this to be an ineffective way to organize, because of the need for information to flow across the entire organization regardless of geography.

  2. Log in as a zone manager.

  3. Create a few forums in the zone workspace that are accessible to all users in your organization (for example "company-wide discussion" or "policies and procedures").

  4. Create manager accounts for each workspace to be created.

    For example, if one of your job functions is "contract bidding," then you can create a user account called contract-bid-manager. And so on.

  5. Create a workspace and assign ownership to the manager account you created in step 3.

  6. Create user groups to control access.

    By creating three or four groups that have a specific kind of access, you can grant someone access to the workspace and all its resources merely by adding their username to a group. Assuming again that you are working in the "contract bidding" job function, we recommend group names such as these:

    • contract-bid-visitors

    • contract-bid-participants

    • contract-bid-moderators

    • contract-bid-managers

  7. Add forums to the new workspace.

  8. Use the ACL tables to grant the groups access to the workspace.

    Topic 6 provides examples of working with access-control list (ACL) tables.

  9. Add users to the appropriate groups.

  10. Repeat steps 5 through 9 for each workspace.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Step list

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
As mentioned, this structure requires significant effort toward the beginning of the process, but it saves time and effort later. This structure eliminates the need to enter every discussion forum, calendar, or chat room individually to grant or deny access to a person. You manage access by manipulating group membership.

For example, if a workspace needs a new discussion forum or chat room, then the user logged in as the workspace manager can create it (because you designated that username as the "owner" of the workspace). If the workspace manager wants to allow a user to participate in all of the forums in the workspace, then the manager adds that user's name to the workspace's "participants" group. If the manager changes her mind, she can delete the user's name from the "participants" group and add it to the "visitors" group. Automatically, this change to the group membership is applied to every discussion forum, calendar, and chat room in the workspace.

The use of a single username to manage a workspace has the following advantages:

  • When you assign ownership of a workspace to a user, this user automatically has the right to manage all of the forums in the space (including the right to create new forums). If you assign workspace-management rights to a group, then you have to access each discussion forum, calendar, and chat room individually within the workspace to assign the group management rights. Using a single user account saves time and effort.

  • If a workspace manager leaves the company, change the password, and give the new password to the next workspace manager. People may leave, but the management account stays constant.

Finally, this structure assumes that the zone workspace is open and accessible to all registered users in your organization. Of course, if this does not meet your needs, you can create a set of groups for the zone workspace just as you did for the other workspaces. Then, grant privileges to the groups in each of the discussion forums, calendars, and chat rooms in the zone workspace, and add users to the appropriate groups.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Summary

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
The enterprise organization that developed this structure is an international company that wanted to get people interacting who would normally not talk to each other, either because of geography or job-title boundaries. This design emphasizes a single place in which users in a large area of job function (this organization calls these job functions "communities of practice") can obtain help with questions and problems, and it involves the systematic archival of "problems solved" into subject-matter areas for easy look up later.

The enterprise organization developed this structure after three years of using SiteScape's collaboration products. The structure serves approximately 7,000 users in three primary user communities. The organization estimates that their users spend approximately 1/2 hour to 2 hours a week using SiteScape's collaboration products.

If you are developing a collaboration solution for an organization of similar size and for a similar activity level, we recommend that you consider implementing several installations of our SiteScape Forum product on your Intranet (in other words, several zones located on different server machines).

If you are developing a solution for a smaller organization, you still may find great value in using the "single point of entry" concept within a single zone.

This section presents very high-level steps that you need to follow to implement this structure. However, there are many discrete management tasks to perform to implement any one step. Also, this section does not provide information on how to delegate management of zones, workspaces, and forums (discussions, calendars, and chat rooms). For information on delegating management, see the previous reply ("Structured by Job Function").
SS_FolderEntries.title: Structured using a single point of entry

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
The following are steps required to implement this workspace structure (they are explained in more detail in the Getting the Most Out of Forum book):

  1. List several primary job functions.

    Keep this list to one, two, or three items. These are the tasks performed by your organization that are central to your mission statement.

    For example, a networking computer company might list the following: Hubs, Routers, and Networking Software.

  2. List secondary job functions.

    Examples include the following: Finance, Human Resources, Marketing, Sales, Testing, and so on.

  3. Create zone workspaces for primary and secondary job functions.

  4. Create a "queries" discussion forum in each of the zone workspaces for primary job functions.

  5. Define a workflow process that sends e-mail notifications to "experts" whenever someone adds a new entry to the "queries" discussion forum.

    This ensures that at least a few knowledgeable people can begin working on the problem in a timely fashion. The workflow would also include a state for "closed" or "answered" so that people know when the querie is no longer active.

  6. Create archival discussion forums by subject matter.

    Using the previous example, within the "Hubs" area, there may be a dozen or more sub-categories of information that have meaning to the participants in that job area. These discussion forums will contain the answered questions and will form a "knowledge repository" for quick look up.

  7. Zone managers of the primary workspaces archive (move) answered queries to the archival forums.

    In this way, the "queries" discussion forum never gets too crowded and contains only the questions that still need answering.

  8. Zone managers of the secondary workspaces monitor the primary ones and copy any applicable items into the secondary zone.

    So, for example, employees working in the Sales or Human Resources zones will read only the technical information that pertains to their jobs (because their zone managers copied the information from the primary workspaces into their workspaces).
SS_FolderEntries.title: High-level steps

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
As mentioned at the beginning of this section, the purpose of this design is "cross fertilization." For example, let's say that a Hub project in Egypt has a problem and posts a note in the Hubs "Queries" discussion forum. Then, a Hub engineer in Seattle who had the same problem while developing a product last year can share the solution. This saves time and money, and it increases the collective knowledge of the organization. This is a quote from the member of the organization that developed this structure: "It was like having 30 years of experience by your side."

As another example, a Routers team in Spain may post a configuration proposal in the "Queries" discussion forum and ask for review comments. A team in Toronto can post a configuration they developed--at great pain and cost--a year earlier. The Spanish team was able to re-use the knowledge, avoid costly mistakes, and develop a configuration in a fraction of the time it would have taken if they had developed it alone. Members of the organization that developed this structure stated that one sharing of a design proposal saved their company $1 million.

Clearly, this section did not provide all of the implementation details of such a structure. You still need to determine how to delegate management and how to create subject-matter repositories. However, we hope that this section gives you some ideas about how to get started in developing a "single point of entry" structure of workspace hierarchies.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Summary

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
When someone installs Forum and then views this discussion, that person may feel slightly lonely; by default, that person is the only user who can access and participate in this forum.

The following replies tell you how you can allow another user and another group of users to access this forum.

It is our hope that you, your zone managers, your workspace managers, and your forum managers will continue to add topics to this discussion, sharing knowledge and helping each other with the task of managing the Forum software.

Thank you for choosing SiteScape and its collaboration products!
SS_FolderEntries.title: Expanding access to this forum

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
The easiest way to allow another user to particpate in this forum is to add the person's username to the SSF Administrators group. (By default, members of this group are allowed to participate here.)

Remember that users that you add to this group become zone managers. Since this is a very powerful position, please choose people wisely, and limit the number of people you add to this group.

Here are the steps required to add a user to the SSF Administrators group:

  1. Click on the Workspace tab to view the workspace page.

  2. Click on the Wizards toolbar item (click on the Click-Wizards-Toolbar-Item.gif link in the Attachments section).

    Wizards are web pages that provide you with additional assistance with the most common of managerial tasks. The items at the top (Create a discussion forum and Invite users to the zone) are tasks that new zone managers will want to perform.

    The items listed under the Create a discussion forum are called specialized forums. These are customized discussion forums that are designed to perform a specific task, such as keeping track of business contacts, tracking resumes, implementing a Help desk application, and more.

    The remaining sections on the "Wizard menu" page assist you in the creation or modification of Forum objects.

    If you are unsure about a link on this page, click on the plus sign ( + ) next to the link, and view a brief description of the wizard. To collapse the Help information again, click on the minus sign ( - ) next to the linked title.

  3. Click on the Modify a group link (click on the Modify-Group-Link.gif link in the Attachments section).

  4. Click on the radio button next to the SSF Administrators group, and click on the Next button (click on the SSF-Administrators-Group.gif link).

  5. On the "Modify a group"/"Group title" page, click on the Next button to skip it.

  6. On the "Modify a group"/"Search for user names" page, use one of three methods for selecting user names (listing all users in your zone, listing all users whose usernames begin with a certain character, or listing all usernames that match a search string).

    If you are sure of the person's username, type it in the "Search text" box located toward the bottom of the page, click on the Search button next to the text box, and then follow the instructions in the next paragraph for adding that person's name to the group.

    Click on the The-Search-For-Users.gif link in the Attachments section. This picture shows an example of how to use this Search page. It is the result of clicking on the T link to list all people whose usernames begin with the letter "T." Then, click or Ctrl click on the name or names of the users you want to add to the group (in the example, only one name, "Tutorial--Joe Smith"). Then, click on the Add button, which adds Joe's username to the Selected Users box. When the Selected Users box contains the names of all of the people whom you want to be zone managers, then click on the Next button at the bottom of the page.

  7. On the "Modify a group"/"Summary for the group" page, review the list of names. If it is not correct, click on the Back button, and search, select, or delete usernames. If the list is correct, click on the Finish button, and complete your use of the wizard pages.
SS_FolderEntries.title: Allowing another user to participate in this forum

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
As discussed in Topic 5, it is common to delegate the management of workspaces or forums, and it is common to do this using a group. If you use this method of delegating the management of Forum resources, then it would be helpful to have members of your management groups participate in this forum.

To allow the members of another group to participate in this forum, do the following:

  1. In this discussion forum, click on the Tools toolbar item (click on the Click-Tools-Item.gif link in the Attachments section).

  2. Click on the Administration menu item (click on Menu-Item-For-Administration.gif).

    Forum displays the Administration Tools for Managing SiteScape Forum page.

  3. In the Security row of the table, click on the Set Access Controls link (click on Set-Access-Controls-Link.gif).

    Forum displays the Control Access to Managing SiteScape Forum page.

  4. Click on the existing group link located toward the top of the page (click on The-Existing-Group-Link.gif).

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
A Forum workspace is a work area containing collaboration tools (described in detail in the next reply) and a group of people working toward a common goal. A workspace can be a designated work area for a company, a department, or a project team.

After you log into Forum, you automatically are in the zone workspace. This is the workspace that everyone in your organization can access. Your Forum manager may or may not decide to create additional workspaces.

On the workspace page, Forum displays the title of the current workspace, a list of the tools available to you in this workspace, and a list of other workspaces available to you. To see pictures of these parts of a zone workspace page, click on these Attachment links in order: A-Workspace-Title.gif, The-Workspace-Tools.gif, The-Workspaces-Available.gif.

Using the example in the pictures you have seen so far, let's say that you no longer want to be in the Widget Company Workspace, and you now want to be in the Engineering workspace. Click on the following links to see how to accomplish this task: To-Click-On-Engineering-Link.gif, Workspace-For-Engineering.gif. After you view the Engineering workspace's page, you can access its unique set of tools (in this example, a discussion and a chat room).

After using a discussion forum, chat room, or calendar, you can return to the workspace page by clicking on the Workspace tab. Click on the Workspace-Tab.gif link to see a picture of the location of this tab.

To continue reading "Learning about SiteScape Forum" information, click on the Next Reply toolbar item toward the center of the blue toolbar above. Click on the You-Click-Next-Reply.gif link to see a picture of the location of this link.

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
Forum provides two types of collaboration tools: tracking pages (described later in this tutorial) and forums. Each workspace contains a unique set of the following types of forums:

Discussion Forums
Allow teammates to have conversations within a broad topic area, while users possibly work from different locations and at different times (this is sometimes called having threaded discussions or posting notes) These forums allow you to post topics and replies, document files, URLs, and polls. (This tutorial is contained within a discussion forum.)

Calendars
Allow you to schedule and monitor appointments and important dates. P>

Tasks
Allow you to track your assignments throughout your entire zone. You can use the reminder feature to remind yourself and others of events, deadlines, or meetings.

Meetings
Chat rooms: Allow teammates--who are possibly in various locations--to communicate while everyone participates at the same time (sometimes called synchronous or real-time communication). This form of chat is ideal for online meetings.

Placeware meetings: Allow you to participate in real-time long-distance meetings from within the context of Forum. You can schedule a meeting, invite others to a meeting, enter a meeting, and modify or delete existing meeting entries.

Messaging
Allows you to have a private chat session with another Forum user. This form of chat is convenient for quick, informal messages.

Let's say that you want to view a particular discussion forum. To access a forum, you can either click on the forum's linked title on a workspace page (click on the A-Title-On-Workspace-Page.gif link), or you can click on the tab and select the forum from a drop-down menu (click on the Click-Tab.gif and Select-Menu-Item.gif links, in order).

Click on the Next Reply menu item in the blue toolbar above to continue reading this topic.

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
After you click on the title of a discussion forum on either the workspace page or on the Discussion tab's drop-down menu, Forum displays the top folder page. A folder page can include a folder abstract, which describes the contents of the folder. Click on the A-Folder-Abstract.gif link to see an example of an abstract.

Forum managers can divide the discussion forum's content into subfolders. If a discussion forum's top folder contains subfolders, they are located toward the top of the page. Click on A-Subfolder-List.gif link. To open a subfolder, you can click on its linked title. To navigate back through the folder hierarchy, click on the links in the upper-left corner of the page. Click on the A-Subfolder-Navigation.gif link.

To view an entry (a topic, document, URL, or survey), click on its linked title in the folder listing. Click on the Click-On-Entry-Title.gif link to see a picture of an entry's linked title within the folder listing. The entry line is preceded by a red exclamation point if you have not  seen that entry or a reply to that entry. By default, the entry line in the folder listing includes an icon that indicates the type of entry (the quotation-mark icon indicates a discussion topic), the entry's number, the number of replies made to the entry, its author, and the date when someone last modified the entry.

Forum provides tools that are specific to the type of forum you are using. These tools are located on the left side of the blue toolbar. Click on Toolbar-Discussion-Forum.gif link. While viewing a folder listing, a discussion forum's tools include the following toolbar items:

Add
Allows you to add new entries, replies, and attachments.

Modify/delete
Allows you to modify or delete the entries that you have created.

Tools
Allows you to change display options, set notifications, set seen entries, set entries unseen, or enable an entry for online chat.

Next unseen
Steps you one by one through each of the entries in the discussion Forum that you have not yet viewed.  

List unseen
Produces a list of all of the entries in the discussion forum that you have not yet viewed.

Search forum
Searches only the discussion forum you are currently viewing.

The information provided here is a very basic introduction to discussion forums. To read more about the powerful features offered with this application, please review the files in the Forum Help system after you have completed the tutorial.

SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
In addition to forums and tracking pages, Forum also offers you zone tools. Regardless of the current workspace or forum, links to these tools are consistently present just above the blue toolbar, in the upper-right corner of the page (click on the Zone-Tools.gif link).

The zone tools are as follows:

Tracker
Provided in previous versions of Forum so that people could keep track of activity in discussion forums on different server machines. If you need to keep track of discussion forums on only one server machine, we recommend that you use the "My summary" page (described in the next reply).

Web File System
Allows you to store files that you want to move, access, or transfer across the web.

For example, you can place files in your web file system while you are at the office, and you can access them when you work from home. Or, you can place files in a folder in your web file system, and you can make them available to teammates (who could possibly be located around the world).

Site Map
Provides you with a listing of all forums available to you on all workspaces. This page is equivalent to the zone workspace's page with its entire hierarchy expanded.

Search all
Allows you to search for information in any discussion, calendar, or chat room that is located in any workspace in your zone.

Help
Displays the Forum Help system in a separate browser window.

Logout
Logs you out of Forum. (This is primarily used by Forum managers who may need to log out of one user account and log into another one.)

After you have reserved it, download the file, edit it on your computer, upload the edited file back into Forum (you can save the previous version if you want), and then click on the Reserve/Release menu item again to release the document. SS_FolderEntries.description_text:
When you create a topic or reply, Forum offers three formatting options. These options are presented as radio buttons located just below the text box on the HTML form used to create the entry.

The following is a list of these formatting options and why you would choose one over the other:

Automatic (default)
Using this option provides you with the following automatic formatting features:

  • Automatic line wrapping

    When you type a paragraph, do not type any carriage returns until you want to break for another paragraph. Forum makes sure that the entry's text fits within the boundaries of the browser window.

  • Preserved line breaks

    If you type a return of carriage, Forum places a return of carriage into the entry. So, if you want to place text on two adjacent lines, type one line of text, type a carriage return, and type the second line of text. The lines' spacing appears on the entry's page just as it appeared when you typed it, as in the following example:

    One line of text [one carriage return]
    And the next line right under it

    If you want to create a new paragraph, enter two carriage returns in between text (one for a new line, and one for a blank line in between paragraphs), as shown in the following example:

    The last line of the paragraph. [two carriage returns]

    The first line of the next paragraph.

  • Automatic linking of URLs

    If you enter a string that begins with an "http://", then Forum assumes that it is a URL, and it automatically makes the URL a live link in the entry's text.

  • Preserved spacing at the beginning of lines

    If you want to indent a paragraph, you can place spaces at the beginning of each line, and Forum retains those spaces on the entry's page.

  • Elimination of spaces between words

    If you place multiple spaces between words in a sentence, Forum reduces them to a single space.

None
Using this option means that Forum takes what you enter literally and does not apply any formatting. For example, Forum keeps all of the spaces that you enter, and it breaks the lines where you apply carriage returns.

Use this option if you want to apply odd spacing within your sentences (for example, more than one space in between words within the sentence), or if you want to create rough columns of text. (For finer control of column creation, we recommend that you use the HTML option and TABLE tags.)

HTML
Using this option causes Forum to assume that the text you enter into the box is coded in HTML. Use this option when you want to add color to text, to have fine control of multiple columns, to use bolding or italics, to center text, to use header tags, or to use list tags. When using the HTML formatting option, be sure to place P tags in between your paragraphs. (Almost all of the entries in this tutorial were formatted using the HTML option.)

Also, when you use the HTML formatting option, be sure to include closing tags. For example, use the closing tags for list items and for paragraphs.

Legislative Newsletter
February 27, 2004

Comanche Helicopter Program Scratched
The Army announced this week that it is canceling its Comanche Helicopter Program and plans to redirect the funds to other aviation needs. The $39 billion Comanche is the largest item terminated by the Bush administration so far.

The Comanche's major components were to be built at a Boeing Company plant in Philadelphia and a United Technologies Corp. Sikorsky Aircraft facility in Bridgeport, Connecticut. The armed scout helicopter has been in planning and development for two decades. It has survived more than 50 reviews, but has yet to produce a single operational aircraft. Army acquisition officials estimate that it will cost between $450 million to $680 million to terminate the program. However, project managers for the program claim the costs could go as high as $2.7 billion, which acquisition officials claim is "way overstated."

Testifying before the House Armed Services Committee hearing this week, Army Chief of Staff Gen. Peter Schoomaker said the Army is committed to aviation transformation and has received assurances from the White House that money earmarked for Comanche through 2011 would be spent on air assets. Schoomaker and the Acting Secretary of the Army Les Brownlee said $14.6 billion that was to have been spent on the purchase of 121 Comanches between fiscal 2004 and fiscal 2011 would instead be used to purchase 796 aircraft and upgrade another 1400.

Lawmakers have warned that the Pentagon is still facing a serious budget crunch and more major weapons systems are likely to end up on the chopping block. Rep. Roscoe Bartlett, R-Md., Chairman of the House Armed Services Subcommittee on Defense said, "I don't think just cutting this one program will mean we're going to have enough money in the future."


Defense Budget Battles
Members of the House Committee on Appropriations, Subcommittee on Defense said recently that defense spending, which has been untouched since September 11, is no longer off-limits. In a year when Republicans are concerned about a soaring deficit, the $401.7 billion Pentagon budget is an enticing target for non-defense appropriators.

House Budget Chairman Rep. Jim Nussle, R-Iowa, has decided not to spare the proposed spending increased for the 2005 defense funding as he prepares to draft spending guidelines for the coming year.

Committee Chairman Jerry Lewis, R-Calif., predicts that all discretionary spending will be on the table when the fiscal 2005 budget resolution is written. "We anticipate building pressures to try to find money for other programs," Lewis said.

Armed Services Committee Chairman Rep. Duncan Hunter, R-Calif., is joining forces with almost three dozen Republicans in an attempt to repel any attempts to cut the defense budget. "We think it's inappropriate to make any cuts in defense during a time of war, when we're still short on munitions and on new equipment," Hunter said. While Hunter would like to see defense spending increased by $50 billion a year, deficit concerns will make it unlikely.

The House markup for the budget is set for March 10 with floor action the week of March 15. The Senate is scheduled to mark up its version on March 4, with floor action the week of March 8.


Increase Requested for Veterans' Affairs
The House Veterans Affairs Committee recommended that Department of Veterans' Affairs (VA) programs receive an increase of $2.4 billion over the administration's fiscal 2005 spending request.

The 2004 budget resolution was held up by committee members determined to boost funding for the VA. That resolution was finally pushed through after $1.2 billion was added.

Some lawmakers believe the growing deficit along with the attention veteran's issues are receiving because of the elections, will make wrangling over this year's budget similar to 2004.

Adding to the pressure to increase funding for the VA is the coalition of veterans' organizations who announced recently that full funding for veterans health care programs is their top priority.

The veterans groups also want Congress to relinquish their annual responsibility for the VA budget, making it a mandatory program whose budget would be set automatically based on the needs of veterans, not arbitrarily set limits.

Rep Christopher Smith, R-N.J., Chairman of the House VA Committee, expressed his support of the idea in the past, but found little support from other members of Congress. Instead, Smith introduced H.R. 2475, a bill that would create an independent panel to set an annual budget figure which would be included in the President's budget request.

Other legislation, S. 50 and H.R.2318, would provide for a guaranteed adequate level of funding for veterans' health car, but has not gained any traction since it was introduced last year.

By Tech. Sgt. Bob Purtiman

USAFE News Service

RAMSTEIN AIR BASE, Germany (USAFENS) -- As the Combat Fitness program kicks into high gear, airmen worldwide are improving their physical fitness to meet the demands of our combat culture.

Combat Fitness is one of fourteen United States Air Forces in Europe Combat and Special Interest Programs that provide for the training, morale, health and fitness of USAFE personnel and their family members in preparation to maintain and sustain required readiness levels to meet peacetime and wartime taskings.

Air Force members stationed in Europe now have a Web site that is the source of current fitness and sports information throughout the entire command. Combatfitness.org went live in January.

“If judged by the number of hits, combatfitness.org is a huge success,” said Debra Ponzio, USAFE Fitness and Sports manager. “We had 64,040 hits in January and 85,371 in February.

“Combatfitness.org is a consolidation of fitness information from the Air Force chief of staff level to our USAFE programs to local initiatives,” she explained. “It also provides a central hub for our USAFE FitLinxx initiative.”

USAFE has the largest sports championship program in the Air Force and the site contains the most up-to-date information on each sport.

Schedules, results, and application information for all sports from USAFE to AIRNORTH Championships, Air Force training camps to Armed Forces, National and CISM championships, are listed on the site.

“The whole package of opportunity has people excited to take part,” Ms. Ponzio said. “In this age of technology, it fits with our busy lifestyles. People can use this site to access fitness information and to log in fitness activities from home or work, anytime day or night.”

The site is two months old and it will continue to grow. As the summer sports season begins, more schedules, results and photos will be posted.

“We will also add more fitness recognition and success stories from across the command,” Ms. Ponzio said. “We hope that people will use the site as their USAFE source of current fitness and sports information. Even if people use it primarily as a conduit to their base FitLinxx site, they’ll see the most current news and event information

MECHANICAL (UNBOOSTED) FLIGHT CONTROL SYSTEM

A typical, simple, mechanical (unboosted) flight control system is the one used in flight training aircraft. The flight control surfaces (ailerons, elevators, and rudder) are moved manually through a series of push-pull rods, cables, bell cranks, sectors, and idlers. Figure 9-1 schematically illustrates the elevator portion of a mechanical (unboosted) flight control system. The control stick is mounted in such a way that it can pivot backwards and forwards on its mounting pin. The control stick is connected to a push-pull rod attached to its lower end. As the stick is moved fore and aft, it causes the elevators to be deflected proportionately.

The push-pull tube (rod) that connects to the lowest point of the control stick extends aft to the pulley. Notice that the function of the pulley is to change the direction of the push-pull action from fore and aft to up and down. The second push-pull tube (rod) connects the forward cable sector and the pulley, and causes the sector to rotate according to the stick movements.


Figure 9-1.—Mechanical (unboosted) flight control system.

 From the forward sector, the cables extend back through the aircraft to the aft cable sector. They have been reduced in length so that the remaining essential components of the elevator control system may all be shown in one drawing.

The aft sector is essentially the same as the forward sector, and it acts as a slave to the forward sector. Cables from the forward sector attach to the aft edges of the aft sector. A push-pull tube from the aft sector conncts to the elevator fitting assembly. The elevator fitting assembly, commonly called the elevator "horn," is built onto the elevators and extends outward (and usually downward) from the elevator surface at right angles to the plane of rotation and the chord line of the elevator surfaces. As the fitting assembly is moved fore or aft, the elevators are moved up or down.
